comments.body:
@amitbhanot The idle count available through the MXBean may include connections that are not valid.  Connections are tested upon borrow, and therefore connections "sitting" in the pool may or may not be valid.

If, however, you have an ``idleTImeout`` configured, and a ``minimumIdle`` setting that is less than ``maximumPoolSize ``, you can be reasonable sure that the connections are alive.

If you are trying to detect that the primary AS400 has gone down, I suggest looking primarily at the total pool size.  When a database fails, the pool will quickly exhaust all of the connections.  When a new connection is requested, one will be selected, then tested, and upon failing, evicted from the pool -- and the process repeated very quickly for the remaining connections in the pool.

@sternr Just one more example that occurred to me today:
```java
Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
stmt.execute("INSERT INTO products(name, price) VALUES ('broom', 2.99);" +
             "SELECT * FROM products WHERE name='broom';" +
             "SELECT * FROM orders;");
// process products
ResultSet rs = stmt.getResultSet();
...
// process orders
if (stmt.getMoreResults()) {
   rs = stmt.getResultSet();
   ...
}
```
The point, as above, being that multiple statements can be executed in a single call, one of which may initiate a transaction (which HikariCP has no way of knowing about), and therefore HikariCP *must* assume that the commit state is dirty after *any* SQL execution.

