   }
}
DataSource ds = new DataSourceWithCallback(new HikariDataSource(config), onBeforeConnectionObtained);
```

If you just need to execute statements on-borrow from the pool, the simplest way of doing this is with a _helper_ rather than a _wrapper_.  For example:

``` java
class DbHelper {
   private DataSource delegate;

   Connection getConnection() throws SQLException {
      Connection con = delegate.getConnection();
      con.execute(...);  // your code here
      return con;
   }
}
```

However, if you are constructing a DataSource to pass into another framework (for example, Hibernate), a _wrapper_ class would be necessary.

The question is, what are you trying to achieve, and how does that fit with the standard model of DataSources?  Using hooks, like that provided by C3P0, can be useful but it also locks your application to C3P0.  A similar hook would lock your application to HikariCP.

A good general goal should be an application that is portable across pool implementations.  A _helper_ class or _wrapper_ class will give you that.  A pool-specific _interface_ hook will not.

